				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 13 Aug 2018 04:37:23 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>formatScrooge</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4479312</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">trunkless&nbsp;legs&nbsp;of&nbsp;stone</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">a&nbsp;shattered&nbsp;visage</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p><em>'Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!<br /> Nothing beside remains. Round the decay<br /> Of that colossal Wreck, boundless and bare<br /> The lone and level sands stretch far away.'</em></p> </div> </div> </div> <p>I initially wasn't going to upvote until I saw the footnote password and realized what this was referencing. A very clever and interesting way to apply the moral of Ozymandias as an antimemetic skip. To be fair, I didn't come here from the Series page, so I had no idea that the poem was referenced there.</p> <p>+1</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
