					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-5804852#post-3783821</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-5804852/ura-9611#post-3783821</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 28 Apr 2018 17:38:52 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Apoplexic</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2767424</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">AHHHHHHHHHHHHHH!!!!!</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Hide</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <blockquote> <p><em>Dr. Percy Hussel, RAISA, Overseer Council Maintenance Division</em></p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p><em>RAISA, Overseer Council Maintenance Division</em></p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p><em><strong>RAISA Overseer Maintenance</strong></em></p> </blockquote> <p>I care least about some temporal shenanigan object that needs a screw to contain it. I care little about the staff shoving their way onto O5 by abusing the anomaly. But that ^^ right there is what got me invested in this site. Anomalies are neat, and character stories make you feel; but a well-written article highlighting that the SCPF has this kind of checks-and-balances system in place, or that actually shows them as a functional, multinational organization designed to save the planet and the inherent need to constantly protect the <em>system</em>, wins my vote every time. The SCPF, in any headcanon where they're global and nigh-on all-powerful (I mean, they usually win, right?), would have to be an immense bureaucratic undertaking, and imo there's not nearly enough material on this site that takes that into consideration.</p> </div> </div> </div> <br /> <span style="font-size:60%;">(see I said I get all fangirly over stuff like this!)</span><br /> +1
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
